The general advice that I personally give to anyone who's looking to get involved in a project in any way is to research the project and start trying to answer some basic questions: 
- Does it resonate with you?
- Does its goals align with yours? 
- Do you understand it in a way that allows you to assess whether involving yourself in it (and I'm talking about all kinds of participation, not just the monetary kind) is going to meet your own goals and needs while at the same time staying within the margins of your own personal risk tolerance? 
- Does its timeframe fit within your own planning horizon and expectations?
- Do you feel that the utility of the project -- what it actually aims to *do* -- is achievable and worth involving yourself in?

If the answer to this is "yes", but you're still approaching the token as a financial instrument (something you're going to use for investment/trading and money-making), then the Community Server is the place for you. Welcome aboard Ramen! Of course and let me break down the difference between both in the network that miners are responsible for training machine learning models. If you are one, you receive data from other nodes, perform computations on that data, provide predictions back to the network, and provide your computational power to train and improve the models within the network.

To come to validators, on the other hand, as you might know, play a crucial role in the consensus and validation process of the network, as it is in the space. They evaluate the predictions made by miners and ensure the accuracy and quality of the outputs. Also, validators help maintain the integrity of the network and contribute to the overall trustworthiness of the trained models.

Now, to come on the second, the Bittensor network focuses on the inference side. To wrap-up, the vision is to create a pure market for artificial intelligence, an incentivized arena in which consumers and producers of this valuable commodity can interact in a trustless, open, and transparent context. Imagine Bittensor being like a giant brain giving access to multiple datasets or models at the same place for the end user, you contribute to the network by running a node and participating in the model training process. Your node will receive data from other nodes in the network, perform computation on that data, and then send it back to the network. In other words, the "training data set" is the sum total of the data flowing through the network, and not something you download from a single location in this case, which should give you clear context.

Very soon we will launch functionality that will allow you to benchmark all miners and choose your miner(s) by creating pools - eg: if you are creating a coding app, you can fire some test code questions and see which miners provide the best responses for your use case, then choose the top x of those and only query them in your query. 

You can create multiple pools for different queries and purposes and monitor the performance of your pools over time by re-running benchmarking. There will also be sets of default BitAPAI pools set to allow different choices by devs depending on their priorities (speed, diversity, context length etc).

Hey @k8359 👋 the Bittensor network is more focused on model inference than model training. Even is the model is naturally being slightly fine tuned while being served to the network as time pass.

Utilizing MoE allows for more efficient use of resources during inference, needing only about 280 billion parameters and 560 TFLOPs, compared to the 1.8 trillion parameters and 3,700 TFLOPs required for a purely dense model.

The model is trained on approximately 13 trillion tokens from various sources, including internet data, books, and research papers. To reduce training costs, OpenAI employs tensor and pipeline parallelism, and a large batch size of 60 million. The estimated training cost for GPT-4 is around $63 million.

While more experts could improve model performance, OpenAI chose to use 16 experts due to the challenges of generalization and convergence. GPT-4's inference cost is three times that of its predecessor, DaVinci, mainly due to the larger clusters needed and lower utilization rates. The model also includes a separate vision encoder with cross-attention for multimodal tasks, such as reading web pages and transcribing images and videos.

OpenAI may be using speculative decoding for GPT-4's inference, which involves using a smaller model to predict tokens in advance and feeding them to the larger model in a single batch. This approach can help optimize inference costs and maintain a maximum latency level.

Question. Anyone can answer! If my staked tao does not leave my wallet, which is what a gentleman informed me on here. Is the validator using the tao ? What is the tao being used for ? Can they just take it from me ?

Good question!  The answer is no, the validator can't take your staked tokens. When you delegate to a validator, the validator is using your Tao to earn additional rewards and increase its position on the network.  The validator does not have access to your staked Tao and cannot take them, even if operating maliciously: your Tao is never forfeited nor are the additional gains you receive in the form of Tao at a rate of 82% of that validator’s rate. 

If the validator goes down, both you and the validator stop earning Tao. At that point, you can unstake your Tao (including any gains you earned while validator was running) and the validator keeps their portion of the additional gains from your your Tao (18%).  Your original stake and rewards earned are never in jeopardy and can be unstaked at any time.
